package in most of Linux distributions, the package system installs other packages needed by the package that we are installing. If we uninstall the package, its dependencies might not be uninstalled, these unused dependencies are called orphaned packages.</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\">\n<p>Let&#8217;s see how to remove orphaned packages.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"sect1\">\n<h2 id=\"_archlinux\"><a href=\"https://archlinux.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Archlinux</a></h2>\n<div class=\"sectionbody\">\n<div class=\"listingblock\">\n<div class=\"content\">\n<pre class=\"highlight\"><code class=\"language-bash\" data-lang=\"bash\">pacman -Rsn $(pacman -Qdtq)</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"paragraph\">\n<p>How does the command work?</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"ulist\">\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p><code>pacman -Qdt</code> list all orphaned packages</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><code>pacman -Rsn</code> uninstall the listed packages</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"sect1\">\n<h2 id=\"_debian\"><a href=\"https://debian.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Debian</a></h2>\n<div class=\"sectionbody\">\n<div class=\"listingblock\">\n<div class=\"content\">\n<pre class=\"highlight\"><code class=\"language-bash\" data-lang=\"bash\">apt-get remove --purge $(deborphan)</code></pre>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>","slug":"linux-remove-orphaned-files"}